{"title":"Deep Object-Centric Representations for Generalizable Robot Learning","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Robots need visual perception that generalizes across object instances and clutter while requiring minimal task-specific supervision, so policies can be learned efficiently for real-world manipulation.","method":"Introduce a two-level, object-centric attention framework. A task-independent meta-attention uses a region proposal network (RPN) trained on MSCOCO to produce object hypotheses with locations g(oi) and semantic features f(oi) from a pretrained ImageNet CNN (AlexNet conv5 pooled over proposal crops). A task-specific attention, parameterized by vector(s) W over f(oi), is learned from a few trajectories by predicting next movement using a soft Boltzmann attention with entropy regularization; during policy learning W is fixed and a hard argmax box is used. The attended object coordinates are concatenated with robot state and used by an RL policy (e.g., guided policy search), yielding robust generalization to unseen mugs and clutter."},{"problem":"Practitioners need to control how broadly a robot’s perception and policy generalize (e.g., avoid distractors vs. broaden to a category) without retraining large detectors or collecting extensive labels.","method":"Adjust the task-specific attention using a handful of additional demonstrations: include distractor objects to narrow the attention to a specific instance, or include diverse relevant objects to broaden to a category. Training W to predict demonstrated motion pushes attention onto objects predictive of trajectories, enabling user-controlled scope (e.g., finetuning with a pink mug as distractor to focus on a brown mug; or adding lemons/limes so attention generalizes beyond oranges to citrus)."},{"problem":"Many manipulation tasks depend on multiple objects whose relative positions matter, requiring perception that can jointly localize several task-relevant items and feed a compact state to the policy.","method":"Stack multiple attention vectors in W to attend to several objects simultaneously over the shared meta-attention proposals and semantic features. Learn these attentions from a small set of kinesthetic demonstrations (initialized with example crops), then feed the attended boxes to a guided policy search controller. Demonstrated on a sweeping task (orange into dustpan) with varying object positions, achieving strong performance and robustness to distractors."}]}
